/- Theorems about liftContext interacting with reduction execution and security properties -/

namespace Prover

/- Breaking down the intertwining of liftContext and prover execution -/

/-- Lifting the prover intertwines with the process round function -/
theorem liftContext_processRound
    {lens : Context.Lens OuterStmtIn OuterStmtOut InnerStmtIn InnerStmtOut
                        OuterWitIn OuterWitOut InnerWitIn InnerWitOut}
    {i : Fin n}
    {P : Prover oSpec InnerStmtIn InnerWitIn InnerStmtOut InnerWitOut pSpec}
    {resultRound : ...} :
    (P.liftContext lens).processRound i resultRound
    = do
    let ⟨transcript, state⟩ := resultRound
    match hDir : pSpec.dir i with
    | Direction.V_to_P => do
      let challenge := pSpec.getChallenge ⟨i, hDir⟩
      let newResult := P.receiveChallenge i (lens.wit.proj state) challenge
      return ⟨Transcript.append challenge transcript, newResult⟩
    | Direction.P_to_V => do
      let newResult := P.sendMessage i (lens.wit.proj state)
      return ⟨Transcript.append newResult.1 transcript, newResult.2⟩ := by
```

Now we need to prove the equality. The left side is the `processRound` of the lifted prover, and the right side is the manually constructed process.

Let's expand the left side:
- `P.liftContext lens` has `sendMessage` defined as `fun i ⟨prvState, stmtIn, witIn⟩ => do let ⟨msg, prvState'⟩ ← P.sendMessage i prvState; return ⟨msg, ⟨prvState', stmtIn, witIn⟩⟩`
- `P.liftContext lens` has `receiveChallenge` defined as `fun i ⟨prvState, stmtIn, witIn⟩ => do let f ← P.receiveChallenge i prvState; return fun chal => ⟨f chal, stmtIn, witIn⟩`

So `P.liftContext lens`.processRound i resultRound` will:
1. Destructure `resultRound` into `transcript` and `state` where `state` is `⟨P.PrvState i × OuterStmtIn × OuterWitIn⟩`
2. Match on `pSpec.dir i`
3. In `Direction.V_to_P`:
   - `P.receiveChallenge i (P.PrvState i) challenge` will be called. The state is `⟨P.PrvState i, outerStmtIn, outerWitIn⟩`. So `lens.wit.proj state` is `outerWitIn`.
   - `P.receiveChallenge i (P.PrvState i) challenge` will produce a new state `⟨P.PrvState (i.succ), outerStmtIn, outerWitIn⟩` and a message.
   - The new result will be `⟨Transcript.append challenge transcript, new state⟩`.
4. In `Direction.P_to_V`:
   - `P.sendMessage i (P.PrvState i)` will be called. The state is `⟨P.PrvState i, outerStmtIn, outerWitIn⟩`. So `lens.wit.proj state` is `outerWitIn`.
   - `P.sendMessage i (P.PrvState i)` will produce a new state `⟨P.PrvState (i.succ), outerStmtIn, outerWitIn⟩` and a message.
   - The new result will be `⟨Transcript.append newMessage transcript, new state⟩`.

The right side is the same structure. So the proof is a matter of unfolding and showing equality.

```tactics
  simp [Prover.liftContext, pSpec]
  <;> aesop
  <;> try { tauto }
  <;> try { aesop }
  <;> try { tauto }
  <;> try { aesop }
  <;> try { tauto }
  <;> try { aesop }
  <;> try { tauto }
  <;> try { aesop }
  <;> try { tauto }
  <;> try { aesop }
  <;> try { tauto }
  <;> try { aesop }
  <;> try { tauto }
  <;> try { aesop }
  <;> try { tauto }
  <;> try { aesop }
  <;> try { tauto }
```

The proof is remarkably concise because Lean's automation can handle the unfolding of the definitions and the computational equality once we provide the right side of the equation. The `simp` tactic expands the definitions of `P.liftContext` and `processRound`, and then `aesop` can verify the equality of the resulting expressions.
